			<ns0:name>b...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/105821748722532785568/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Right now (mostly for expedience) Windows clock_gettime with clock ID of CLOCK_MONOTONIC just returns the real time with a little bit of code to ensure that the clock value is indeed monotonically non-decreasing.  This can mislead developers in thinking that CLOCK_MONOTONIC values can be used in other contexts if they develop primarily on Windows, and be surprised when they test on other OSes.

Eventually, we should probably use time-since-boot or some other similar time base on Windows.  But until then, a simple change would be to add an (fixed) offset to the return value, so that the returned value would differ from the CLOCK_REALTIME value.
